deck: Daughter of the evil witch Zamora. She is often referred to as 'The Wicked Witch of the East'.
description:
Origin

Zinna is the daughter of the witch Zamora and twin sister of Lynessa. She took her residence in The Land of Ak, a region in the east of Oz. As such she became known as the Wicked Witch of the East.

Creation

Like most characters of the Grimm Fairy Tales lore, Zinna has her inspiration in fairy tales or literature. Zinna is inspired on the Wicked Witch of the East from L. Frank Baum's children's book The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (1900).

Major Story Arcs

Grimm Fairy Tales Presents Oz

The wolf known as Toto ran away with the Veridian Scepter, which had killed her mother many years ago. He ran from Oz through a portal to Kansas and encountered a helpful Dorothy Gale. Lynessa had tracked down Toto and demanded him back. But Dorothy refused to give him up. Angered, Lynessa magically transported Dorothy's farm to Oz, where her sister Zinna awaited them. In the battle, Dorothy grabbed the Veridian Scepter and killed Zinna with it.

deck: Luminous is favored by the High Evolutionary and is allegedly the sister of Scarlet Witch and Quicksilver.
description:
Origin

In the latest incarnation of the Uncanny Avengers, Luminous appears to Scarlet Witch and Quicksilver as they attempt to find answers concerning their parentage and taunts them as she displays an upgraded combination of their power sets. She has a lofty opinion of herself and is absolutely subservient to the High Evolutionary.

Powers

Luminous wields immense power, able to manipulate Chaos Magic with more accuracy than the Scarlet Witch and (theoretically) capable of accelerating faster than Quicksilver. She has also displayed self-propelled flight and force field construction, but the origin and limitations of these abilities are as of yet unknown.

deck: A wolf born in Oz. When it encountered Dorothy Gale in Kansas, they immediately bonded.
description:
Origin

The wolf who would become known as Toto, was once the companion of the wizard Faedhlan in Oz. The wizard, having the Veridian Scepter in his possession, was chased by Skarabs led by Lynessa. Trapped, the wizard gave the wolf the scepter and ordered it to flee. The wolf went through a portal to Kansas and discovered a helpful Dorothy Gale. She named him Toto. Lynessa had tracked Toto and demanded it back, but Dorothy refused. Angered, Lynessa magically transported Dorothy's whole farm to Oz.

Major Story Arcs

Oz: Age of Darkness

Seventyfive years have passed. Dorothy Gale is now queen of Oz, ruling with Thorne, Scarecrow and Toto by her side. The Dark Queen recovers the Warlord of Oz and sets him loose on Oz. He manages to kill Thorne, Scarecrow and Toto before beheading Dorothy Gale. He then sits on the throne of Oz himself.

Zinna, the evil with from the east of Oz, had created a race of living scarecrows. They were her former enemies and the transformation to scarecrows included removing their brains. Bartleby had been Zinna's unwitting pawn and thus she didn't remove his brain.

Creation

Like most characters of the Grimm Fairy Tales lore, Scarecrow has her inspiration in fairy tales or literature. Scarecrow is inspired on the Scarecrow from L. Frank Baum's children's book The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (1900).

Grimm Fairy Tales Presents Oz

After Zinna's death (killed by Dorothy), townspeople hung Scarecrow on a pole and threatened to burn him alive. He was rescued by Glinda after he shouted he knew the location of Grafft, a wizard Glinda needed to complete the Veridian Scepter.

Oz: Age of Darkness

deck: Aisling's fiancée.
description:
Origin

The undead Iago tricked his way into Aisling's father's kingdom Vallone, seeking employ as a sorcerer. Getting close enough to the royal family, he gave Aisling two choices: accept his proposal or see her family die. Against her will, she chose to wed him. Her father had his best knight take Aisling away from the kingdom the night before the wedding. Orcus, who owed Iago a favor, and his army laid waste to the kingdom. Fearing for her father's life, Aisling returned, but only saw the place in ruins and the people dead.

When Aisling returned years later, Iago was still waiting for her. But this time she had company with her: the Wonderland knight Blake, the dwarf Bolder and the sorceress Druanna. Together, the killed Iago.

deck: Neol is the commander of the Atlantean military forces under king Aquaman and a member of the Atlantean council.
description:
Current Events

Neol is the commander of the Atlantean military forces bearing the title of High Lord of the Armies and a member of the Atlantean council. He serves king Aquaman. He is a tall and powerfully built Atlantean with grey hair, suggesting he is older than Aquaman.

He led a mission searching for Aquaman and Mera in the pocket dimension of Pacifica and also accompanied Aquaman against a threat related to Swamp Thing.

Currently he is in Atlantis, serving in Aquaman's council.

Creation

Neol was created by Aquaman writer Jeff Parker and artist Paul Pelletier. He made his debut in Aquaman #26.

Powers & Abilities

Neol is an Atlantean and possesses their typical superhuman abilities.

Superhuman Strength

Neol like all Atlanteans has some degree of superhuman strength.

Enhanced Durability

Neol like all Atlanteans has some degree of enhanced durability.

Underwater Adaptation

He can function normally underwater and is able to withstand the high pressures and extreme temperatures of the deep.

Leadership

He is the leader and of the Atlantean military and a member of the Atlantean council. He is frontline leader and directly engages in combat.

Trained Warrior

Neol is trained in Atlantean warfare. He has knowledge of military weapons and vehicles.

Weaponry & Equipment

Atlantean Energy Riffle

Neol is seen wielding an Atlantean energy riffle.

deck: Koah is the Atlantean Elder of Law and a member of the Atlantean council.
description:
Current Events

Koah is the Atlantean Elder of Law and a member of the Atlantean council. He serves king Aquaman. He is older than Aquaman and seems to distrust the surface world. He has extended knowledge of Atlantean history and law and is one of Aquaman's closest advisers.

He escorted queen Mera and captain Tula in the lower more xenophobic levels of Atlantis while investigating an assassination attempt.

His clothes have very distinct yellow shoulder pads with black spots, characteristics of Aquaman's villain Fisherman . In Aquaman #24 the statue representing one of the seven kingdoms of Atlantis is of a man wearing Fisherman's characteristic yellow and black helmet. No further connection has been revealed yet.

Creation

Koah was created by Aquaman writer Jeff Parker and artist Paul Pelletier. He made his debut in Aquaman#26.

Powers & Abilities

Koah is an Atlantean and possesses their typical superhuman abilities.

Superhuman Strength

Koah like all Atlanteans has some degree of superhuman strength.

Enhanced Durability

Koah like all Atlanteans has some degree of enhanced durability.

Underwater Adaptation

He can function normally underwater and is able to withstand the high pressures and extreme temperatures of the deep.

Intellect (Law and History)

He is the Elder of Law and an expert on the subject. He also has extended knowledge of Atlantean history.

Weaponry & Equipment

Atlantean Staff

He carries a staff that can create a short range vibration wave.

deck: A young Padawan apprentice of Depa Billaba during the fall of the Old Republic. He became a Jedi rebel afterwards. Leads a Rebel group alongside with Hera Syndulla, he is also the master of Ezra Bridger.
description:
Origin

Kanan Jarrus was a young boy whom was being trained to become a Jedi Knight during the final days of the old Republic.

Creation

Kanan Jarrus was created for the Star Wars: Rebels television series, but was brought into comics when Marvel re-acquired the rights to publish once more. His first comic book appearance was in Kanan - The Last Padawan issue 1 (2015).

Major Story Arcs

Dark Times

While Caleb Dume was with on a mission with his Jedi Master, Senator Palpatine executed Order 66, which caused the clone troopers whom had stood with them for years, to turn against the Jedi. Caleb had to flee and went underground, fearing for his life since the Jedi had been made enemies of the newly formed Empire.

While in hiding, he rid himself of his name and disguised himself as a new person. He became nameless and worked with Janus Kasmir as a black market dealer, but not for long. The clones that turned on him never stopped searching and during one deal, they attacked and stole him. He fought his way out of their ship and detonated it, killing the clones he once fought with for years.

Caleb then realized that as long as he is with Janus, Janus will never be safe. So he left him and joined a group of rebels under the new name Kanan Jarrus.

Other Media

Star Wars: Rebels animated series

Kanan Jarrus appears in the new animated series, in which he is the star of the show.
